## What I built

A FastAPI multi-tenant SaaS skeleton using **SQLAlchemy 2.0 + SQLite**, **JWT** auth, and **bcrypt** password hashing.

```
app/
  main.py        # FastAPI app, creates tables, mounts routers, /health
  config.py      # env-overridable settings (DB url, JWT secret)
  database.py    # engine + session + get_db dependency
  models.py      # Organisation, User, Project  (all tenant rows carry org_id)
  schemas.py     # Pydantic request/response models
  security.py    # bcrypt hashing + JWT encode/decode
  deps.py        # get_current_user (token‚Üíuser) + require_admin
  routers/
    auth.py      # POST /auth/signup, POST /auth/login, GET /auth/me
    users.py     # admin-only org-scoped user management
    projects.py  # sample resource: org-scoped CRUD
requirements.txt ¬∑ README.md ¬∑ .env.example ¬∑ .gitignore
```

## How the requirements map

- **Organisations sign up** ‚Üí `POST /auth/signup` creates the org + its first user (an **admin**) and returns a token.
- **Each org has its own users & data** ‚Üí every `User` and `Project` row carries an `org_id`; email is unique *per org* (`UniqueConstraint(org_id, email)`), so the same email can exist in different orgs.
- **Strict isolation** ‚Üí the JWT encodes both `user_id` and `org_id`; every query filters by the caller's `org_id`, and single-record lookups return **404** (not 403) for other orgs' ids, so foreign ids aren't even confirmed to exist.
- **Org-scoped login** ‚Üí `POST /auth/login` requires `org_slug` + `email` + `password`.
- **Org admin role** ‚Üí `require_admin` guards user-management endpoints; includes a "can't demote/delete the last admin" safeguard.
- **Sample resource** ‚Üí `projects` with full CRUD, all org-scoped.
- **Database** ‚Üí SQLite by default (`app.db`, auto-created); switch to Postgres by setting `DATABASE_URL`.

## Run it locally on port 5087

```powershell
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
pip install -r requirements.txt
uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 5087 --reload
```

Then open **http://localhost:5087/docs**. The README has a copy-paste `curl` walkthrough that proves isolation: Org B logging in sees `[]` instead of Org A's project, and `GET /projects/1` returns `404`.

A couple of robustness choices worth noting: I used `HTTPBearer` (paste the token into Swagger's "Authorize" button) since login is JSON-based; capped passwords at bcrypt's 72-byte limit; and used lower-bound version pins so the dependencies resolve wheels cleanly on your Python 3.14.

