## Security mapping (OWASP Top 10)

- **Access control / IDOR** ‚Äî every query filters by `org_id`; a single `_load_owned_project` chokepoint enforces tenant scope + per-member ownership (guessed IDs ‚Üí 404). Admin routes gated by explicit role check; admins can only ever act within their own org.
- **SQL injection** ‚Äî all DB access via SQLAlchemy ORM (bound parameters); no string-built SQL.
- **Password storage** ‚Äî bcrypt with per-password random salt; length-bounded to avoid silent 72-byte truncation.
- **XSS** ‚Äî Jinja2 autoescaping on for context-aware output encoding; all form input validated/normalised server-side.
- **CSRF** ‚Äî synchronizer-token pattern with constant-time compare, required on every state-changing POST (login, logout, signup, project create/edit/delete, user create/delete).
- **Session cookies** ‚Äî signed, `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (when `SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE=true`); session reset on login (fixation protection).
- **Security headers** ‚Äî CSP, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `nosniff`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`, HSTS over HTTPS; interactive docs disabled.
- **Error handling** ‚Äî custom handlers return generic pages; full detail logged server-side, never sent to clients.
- **Secrets** ‚Äî `SECRET_KEY`/`DATABASE_URL` read from env; app refuses to start without a ‚â•32-char `SECRET_KEY`.

Two notes worth flagging: `.env.example` ships `SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE=false` so cookies work over plain-HTTP localhost ‚Äî **set it to `true` for any HTTPS/production deploy**. And as documented in the README's "Production notes," login/signup rate-limiting and MFA are deliberately left as next steps for a real deployment.

